One thing I keep coming back to

This idea doesn’t only make money.

It makes golf more social.

Right now, golfers remember rounds through scorecards, photos, or stories.

This creates a visible, tactile record of where you’ve played and what you’ve accomplished.

Someone sees your bag and says:

“You’ve played Bandon? How was it?”

or

“You broke 80? Nice.”

That’s a conversation starter, and conversations build community.

That community aspect is what could turn a simple accessory into a category.

So my next-step recommendation is very simple:

Don’t spend money building inventory yet. Spend time proving that golfers and courses genuinely want to collect and display these. If that validation is strong, everything else—bags, partnerships, and licensing—becomes much easier to justify.